4)platelts: stops blood by clotting blood:

| **Feature**                | **Arteries**                                                 | **Veins**                                                    | **Capillaries**                                                                          |
| -------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **1. Function**            | Carry **blood away from the heart**                          | Carry **blood toward the heart**                             | Connect arteries and veins; allow **exchange of materials** between blood and body cells |
| **2. Type of blood**       | Usually carry **oxygenated blood** (except pulmonary artery) | Usually carry **deoxygenated blood** (except pulmonary vein) | Blood changes from oxygenated to deoxygenated                                            |
| **3. Wall thickness**      | **Thick, muscular, and elastic** walls                       | **Thin** walls, less muscular                                | **Very thin (one cell thick)** walls                                                     |
| **4. Lumen (inner space)** | **Narrow lumen**                                             | **Wide lumen**                                               | Very **narrow** â€” just wide enough for one red blood cell                                |
| **5. Valves**              | **No valves**                                                | **Valves present** to prevent backflow                       | **No valves**                                                                            |
| **6. Blood pressure**      | **High pressure**                                            | **Low pressure**                                             | â€”                                                                                        |
| **7. Example**             | Aorta, pulmonary artery                                      | Vena cava, pulmonary vein                                    | Capillary networks in organs                                                             |

Blood vessels: here blood pipe that flow through whole body:

**Heart: a muscular organ roughly the size of fist that acts as pump to circulate the body through the body:
The heart is a muscular organ about the size of your fist.
It acts as a pump that continuously circulates blood throughout the body, supplying oxygen and nutrients and removing carbon dioxide and wastes.

It lies slightly tilted to the left side of the chest, protected by the rib cage.

** Strcuture of hearts:
| **Side**       | **Upper Chamber (Atria)**                                                 | **Lower Chamber (Ventricles)**                                 |
| -------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Right side** | **Right atrium** â€“ receives **deoxygenated blood** from body (via veins). | **Right ventricle** â€“ pumps deoxygenated blood to **lungs**.   |
| **Left side**  | **Left atrium** â€“ receives **oxygenated blood** from lungs.               | **Left ventricle** â€“ pumps oxygenated blood to **whole body**. |

** valves in heart:
| **Valve name**              | **Location**                                 | **Function**                               |
| --------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
| **Tricuspid valve**         | Between right atrium and right ventricle     | Prevents backflow of blood to right atrium |
| **Pulmonary valve**         | Between right ventricle and pulmonary artery | Prevents backflow from artery to ventricle |
| **Bicuspid (mitral) valve** | Between left atrium and left ventricle       | Prevents backflow to left atrium           |
| **Aortic valve**            | Between left ventricle and aorta             | Prevents backflow from aorta to ventricle  |

blood connected with heart:
| **Vessel**                          | **Carries**        | **To/From**                 |
| ----------------------------------- | ------------------ | --------------------------- |
| **Vena cava (superior & inferior)** | Deoxygenated blood | From body â†’ Right atrium    |
| **Pulmonary artery**                | Deoxygenated blood | Right ventricle â†’ Lungs     |
| **Pulmonary veins**                 | Oxygenated blood   | Lungs â†’ Left atrium         |
| **Aorta**                           | Oxygenated blood   | Left ventricle â†’ Whole body |

ðŸ”„ 4. Circulation of Blood (Double Circulation)

Human beings have double circulation, meaning blood passes through the heart twice in one complete cycle.

(a) Pulmonary Circulation

Right ventricle â†’ Pulmonary artery â†’ Lungs â†’ Pulmonary veins â†’ Left atrium
ðŸ‘‰ Carries deoxygenated blood to lungs and brings back oxygenated blood.

(b) Systemic Circulation

Left ventricle â†’ Aorta â†’ Body â†’ Vena cava â†’ Right atrium
ðŸ‘‰ Carries oxygenated blood to body and brings back deoxygenated blood.

ðŸ’“ 5. Working of the Heart (Heartbeat Process)

Blood enters the right atrium from the body (via vena cava).

It moves into the right ventricle.

Right ventricle pumps it to the lungs for oxygenation (via pulmonary artery).

Oxygenated blood returns to the left atrium (via pulmonary veins).

It moves to the left ventricle, which then pumps blood to the entire body through the aorta.

Each heartbeat = one complete contraction and relaxation of the heart.

| **Disease**         | **Description**                                           |
| ------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Heart attack**    | Blockage of blood flow to heart muscles (lack of oxygen). |
| **Hypertension**    | High blood pressure, makes the heart work harder.         |
| **Atherosclerosis** | Fat deposits narrow the arteries.                         |
| **Arrhythmia**      | Irregular heartbeat.                                      |

**About of LYMPH***
1)Lymph is a colorless fluid (slightly yellowish) found in the body.

2)It is formed from tissue fluid that leaks out of blood capillaries.

3)It carries white blood cells (lymphocytes) â€” helps in fighting infections.

4)It helps in transport of fats and fat-soluble vitamins from the intestine.

5)It returns excess tissue fluid back into the bloodstream.

6)It flows through lymph vessels and lymph nodes.

7)Lymph nodes filter germs and dead cells â€” part of the immune system.

*****Transportation in plants:****

slow transportaion sysem 1)plant do not move 2)have large propetion of dead cells in many tissue hence they have low energy needs and low transportaion system:
XYLEM and PHLOEM:

| **Feature**                 | **Xylem**                                                                | **Phloem**                                                         |
| --------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| **1. Function**             | Transports **water and minerals** from roots to other parts of the plant | Transports **food (sugars)** from leaves to all parts of the plant |
| **2. Direction of flow**    | **One direction** â€” upward only (root â†’ leaves)                          | **Both directions** â€” upward and downward                          |
| **3. Type of transport**    | **Physical process** (no energy used)                                    | **Active process** (requires energy)                               |
| **4. Main components**      | Tracheids, vessels, xylem fibers, xylem parenchyma                       | Sieve tubes, companion cells, phloem fibers, phloem parenchyma     |
| **5. Dead or living cells** | Mainly **dead cells** (except xylem parenchyma)                          | Mainly **living cells** (except phloem fibers)                     |
| **6. Thickness of walls**   | **Thick and lignified** walls                                            | **Thin cell walls**                                                |
| **7. Role in plant**        | Helps in **water conduction** and **provides mechanical support**        | Helps in **food transport** (translocation)                        |

